\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Operation 1.10
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Operation-1.10"

\end_inset

:
 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{I_{\alpha}\}_{\alpha\in A}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of ideals of a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap_{\alpha\in A}I_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is an Ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and is the largest ideal contained in all of the ideals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Note:
 
\series default
We know that the intersection is an ideal,
 since for any 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\cap_{\alpha\in A}I_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

,
 we get that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\alpha}\in\{I_{\alpha}\}_{\alpha\in A}:r\in I_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\alpha\in A:I_{\alpha}\text{ is an ideal}$
\end_inset

,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall a\in R\forall I_{\alpha}\in\{I_{\alpha}\}_{\alpha\in A}:ar\in I_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

,
 hence we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $ar\in\cap_{\alpha\in A}I_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 A simillar argument works for the right multiplication,
 hence making it clear how 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap_{\alpha\in A}I_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal.
 
\end_layout

