\series bold
Lemma 3.8
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Lemma-3.8"

\end_inset

:
 
\series default
given 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 a field,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k[x]$
\end_inset

 is a PID.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof:
 
\series default
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be any ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[x]$
\end_inset

,
 then conside 
\begin_inset Formula $0\neq f(x)\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall g\in I:\deg f\le\deg g$
\end_inset

.
 Hence consider teh divison of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 thus we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists r$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g=qf+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg r<\deg f$
\end_inset

.
 It is to be noted that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $qf\in I$
\end_inset

,
 thus we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=g-qf\in I$
\end_inset

.
 The only such polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg r<\deg f$
\end_inset

 is the zero polynomial,
 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus getting 
\begin_inset Formula $g=qf$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence we have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall g\in I,\exists q\in k[x]:g=qf$
\end_inset

,implying 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left(f\right).$
\end_inset

Therefore showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $k[x]$
\end_inset

 is a PID.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\square$
\end_inset


\end_layout

