\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proposition 3.10
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Proposition-3.10"

\end_inset

:
 
\series default
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be an algebrically closed field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset k[x]$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is maximal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left(x-c\right)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof:
 
\series default
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is an algebrically closed field,
 thus consider 
\begin_inset Formula $k[x].$
\end_inset

We already know that 
\begin_inset Formula $k[x]$
\end_inset

 is a PID (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand labelonly
reference "Lemma-3.8"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset k[x]$
\end_inset

 be an ideal,
 hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists f\in I$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left(f\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left(x-c\right)$
\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in k$
\end_inset

,
 then we get,
 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand labelonly
reference "Proposition-2.4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k[x]}{\left(x-c\right)}\cong k
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a field,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k[x]}{\left(x-c\right)}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Thus by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand labelonly
reference "Definition-3.1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left(x-c\right)$
\end_inset

 is maximal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

 is maximal.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is algebrically closed,
 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists c\in k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(c)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus consider the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the divison of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x-c$
\end_inset

 and get that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=q(x-c)+r
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(c)=0$
\end_inset

,
 we get that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=q(x-c)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus for any 
\begin_inset Formula $pf\in\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $pf=pq(x-c)\in\left(x-c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore showing taht 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f\right)\subset\left(x-c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

 is maximal,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-c\right)=k[x]$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-c\right)=\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-c\right)\neq\left(f\right),$
\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall q\in k[x]:q(x-c)\neq c$
\end_inset

,
 hence we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-c\right)=\left(f\right)=I$
\end_inset

.
 therefore showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-c\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is maximal if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left(x-c\right)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in k$
\end_inset

,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 an algebrically closed field,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\square$
\end_inset


\end_layout

